dataIdInfo.idAbs:
This dataset includes changes in land cover throughout Washington State, specifically areas of tree loss and development. Changes are represented as polygons and include qualitative descriptions and quantitative assessments of changes. Attributes provide details about causes of change (Change Agents), types of changes observed (e.g. canopy loss, impervious surface gain), area of change, and time period for when the change occurred. The change locations were identified from analyzing high resolution (1-meter) NAIP imagery, allowing changes as small as a single tree or new home to be identified.

This dataset covers most of Western Washington and several counties in Eastern Washington. Coverage is split along county and/or WRIA boundaries and the time periods for change locations vary by county and/or WRIA. All areas in the dataset were assessed for changes between 2011 and 2017; additionally, some locations include changes as early as 2006 or as recent as 2021.

Visit https://hrcd-wdfw.hub.arcgis.com/ or email HRCD@dfw.wa.gov for more information on how the data is created, accuracy information, tutorials, user guides, and current coverage information.

This dataset is updated regularly (about twice a year) with more recent years of change, new counties / WRIAs, or both. This copy of the data was updated in January 2024.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The data is intended to help monitor and assess trends in land cover change over time. The polygons represent areas which have experienced change. These changes primarily include significant loss of tree cover or areas that have been converted to "permanent" human use (i.e. roads, buildings). Data have been created for areas in Washington as funding allows: visit https://hrcd-wdfw.hub.arcgis.com/ for information on past and current funding sources.

dataSource.srcDesc: NAIP acquires digital ortho imagery during the agricultural growing seasons in the continental U.S.. A primary goal of the NAIP program is to enable availability of ortho imagery within one year of acquisition. NAIP provides two main products: 1-meter ground sample distance (GSD) ortho imagery rectified to a horizontal accuracy of within +/- 5 meters of reference digital ortho quarter quads (DOQQ's) from the National Digital Ortho Program (NDOP); and, 2-meter GSD ortho imagery rectified to within +/- 10 meters of reference DOQQs. The tiling format of NAIP imagery is based on a 3.75' x 3.75' quarter quadrangle with a 300 meter buffer on all four sides. NAIP quarter quads are formatted to the UTM coordinate system using NAD83. NAIP imagery may contain as much as 10% cloud cover per tile. Files are generated by compressing NAIP quarter quadrangle tiles that cover a county. MrSID compression, with mosaic option, was used. Target values for the compression ratio are (15:1) and the maximum N-levels are used.

edom.edomvd: Development: Changes primarily caused by permanent additions to the land for human use (i.e. new buildings, roads, driveways). May include new impervious surface, new semi-pervious surface, and/or tree canopy loss.
Forestry: Changes primarily caused by the removal of trees for commercial use (i.e. clear cut, thinning). May include new semi-pervious surface and/or tree canopy loss.
Tree Removal: Changes primarily caused by the general removal of trees for a variety of reasons. May include new semi-pervious surface and/or tree canopy loss.
Stream: Changes primarily caused by natural water action (i.e. stream course changes, stream bank slides, flooding). Does not include removal of grass or shrubs. May include tree canopy loss.

Redevelopment: Changes include the removal of impervious surface (i.e. buildings, roads). May include the replacement of new impervious surface (i.e. removal of a building and adding a new building). May or may not include new impervious surface, new semi-pervious surface, and/or tree canopy loss.

Retention Pond: Changes include the installation of a small man-made water structure designed to satisfy mitigation requirements. May or may not include new impervious surface, new semi-pervious surface, and/or tree canopy loss.

Other, Natural: Changes primarily caused by naturally occurring events which remove tree canopy (i.e. fire, landslide, avalanche, wind, beetle kill). Does not include natural stream-side changes (Value 4). May include tree canopy loss.

Other, Human: Changes primarily caused by miscellaneous human actions (i.e. installation of corrals, poorly defined gravel areas, commercial forest roads, gravel pits, and temporary roads that do not lead to permanent structures. May include new semi-pervious surface and/or tree canopy loss.
